How to improve this? Let's do some pre-processing before thresholding.

In [8]:
Gauss = gaussian(channel_1, sigma=5)
Thresholded = Gauss > threshold_otsu(Gauss) # make sure you apply the Otsu to the Gaussian filtered image!
fig, ax = plt.subplots(1,1,figsize=(10,10))
ax.imshow(Thresholded, cmap='gray')
ax.axis('off');

This looks much better! The Gaussian filter removed the noise, so the Otsu threshold yields much more continuous objects! But still we have a lot of little objects that are probably not cells, and some of our cells have 'holes'. Luckily there are methods that can easily help with that.

In [10]:
Holes_removed = remove_small_holes(Thresholded, area_threshold = 512)
fig, ax = plt.subplots(1,1,figsize=(10,10))
ax.imshow(Holes_removed, cmap='gray')
ax.axis('off');
In [11]:
Small_objects_removed = remove_small_objects(Holes_removed, min_size = 1024)
fig, ax = plt.subplots(1,1,figsize=(10,10))
ax.imshow(Small_objects_removed, cmap='gray')
ax.axis('off');

You may have to play around with the area_threshold and min_size parameters to get the desired effect. This depends heaviliy on your data, camera format, pixel size, etc. But for a simple combination of filters I think the result is already very good! One problem remains, we have quite some touching cells that would be considered by a segmentation algorithm as one object. How do we split them? We will talk about this more once we get to Segmentation.

However, one approach are Morphological filters that typically work on binary (boolean, black/white) images. To understand how those filters work, let's just have a look at a part of the image.

In [12]:
Image_slice = Small_objects_removed[slice(250,350),slice(80,180)]
In [14]:
fig, ax = plt.subplots(1,1,figsize=(5,5))
ax.imshow(Image_slice, cmap='gray')
ax.axis('off');

Let's run 4 common morphological operations, dilation, erosion, closing, opening.

  • dilation increases the size of bright regions.
  • erosion decreases the size of bright regions.
  • closing is a dilation followed by an erosion. Closing can break up bright areas and remove small objects.
  • opening is an erosion followed by a dilation. Opening can connect dark areas.

The scikit-image version of these filters uses a structuring element to apply the algorithm. This can for example be a round area. We can use the function disk for this purpose.

In [15]:
morphological_filters = [dilation, erosion, closing, opening]
parameters = [disk(13), disk(13), disk(13), disk(13)]
fig, ax = plt.subplots(1,len(morphological_filters)+1,figsize=((len(morphological_filters)+1)*7, 7))
ax[0].imshow(Image_slice, cmap='gray')
ax[0].axis('off')
ax[0].set_title('original')
ax[0].title.set_size(28)
i=1
for morphological_filter, parameter in zip(morphological_filters, parameters):
    filtered = morphological_filter(Image_slice, parameter)
    ax[i].imshow(filtered, cmap='gray')
    ax[i].axis('off')
    ax[i].set_title(morphological_filter.__name__)
    ax[i].title.set_size(28)
    i=i+1
plt.tight_layout()

Note how dilation and erosion change the area of the thresholded objects whereas closing and opening roughly aim to keep the area but are effective in connecting objects ('closing') or breaking up objects ('opening'). So the latter would already be a good approach to separate touching cells! However, we would have to manually determine the optimal parameter for the 'opening' structural element for every data set.
